{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653074"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18561"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18561"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11293"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96189"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10522"},{"type":"tags","id":"10525"},{"type":"tags","id":"11276"},{"type":"tags","id":"11277"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of vermiculation in the ureters?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Voluntary skeletal muscle contractions","Direct sympathetic nerve stimulation","Continuous tonic smooth muscle contraction","Coordinated pacemaker activity from renal pelvis cells","Passive movement due to hydrostatic pressure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordinated pacemaker activity from renal pelvis cells\u003C/strong\u003E represents the correct mechanism. These specialised cells in the renal pelvis generate spontaneous action potentials that spread through gap junctions between smooth muscle cells, creating coordinated waves of contraction that propel urine towards the bladder. These movements occur at a rate of 1-5 contractions per minute. This intrinsic pacemaker mechanism ensures continuous antegrade flow of urine from the kidneys to the bladder against gravity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive movement due to hydrostatic pressure\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient for effective urine transport, as active muscular contractions are required to overcome gravity and anatomical obstacles. \u003Cstrong\u003EDirect sympathetic nerve stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E can modulate ureteric motility but does not directly control the fundamental vermiculation process. \u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous tonic smooth muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E would prevent urine flow rather than facilitate it, as the ureter exhibits rhythmic peristaltic waves rather than maintained tonic contraction. \u003Cstrong\u003EVoluntary skeletal muscle contractions\u003C/strong\u003E play no role since the ureter contains smooth muscle and operates under involuntary control. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ureteric vermiculation is the wave-like contraction of smooth muscle that propels urine from kidneys to bladder.","Pacemaker cells in the renal pelvis initiate spontaneous action potentials that spread through the ureter.","Ureteric peristalsis occurs at a rate of 1-5 contractions per minute to maintain urine flow."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 26; pg. 327.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96189"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18561"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96189"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T11:52:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:52:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11293"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"},"relationships"